Consider a world where a significant proportion of financial activity is conducted over lightning or second-layer scaling solutions

not on-chain.

not through an intermediary.

How do we guard against (or even perceive?) systemic financial risks?

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
Is this a case of academic concern-trolling? We've certainly seen this before in crypto.

Or can Omarova see the likely future that will be if Lightning and other second-layer scaling solutions thrive?

name: Marco Santori
tweet: Do you think this right? Is this how lightning works? What information that *ought* to be available to regulators is obscured by lightning?

name: Marco Santori
tweet: Omarova writes that "technology makes these old dynamics much less visible behind the shining veil of scientific progress."

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
In fact, she thinks this just "replicates the familiar patterns of margin trading and collateralized borrowing that enable financial asset speculation." 

I.e.: Lightning just creates Wall Street on steroids.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
"what gets recorded in the publicly distributed ledger can simply be a net result of multiple trades run by dealers... that provides precious little insight into market activity underlying it."

Wait if we're regulators we don't like this at all.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
"Lightning and similar programs are potentially creating a crucial system-wide capacity for levering and netting of financial transactions ‚Äúoff chain.‚Äù"

Sounds interesting, but...

tweet:

name: Marco Santori
tweet: Doing good crypto policy is just really, really hard. You should file your own comment and tell the regulators how to do it better. You can do it right now, online, without even identifying yourself, at https://t.co/h4f3o3Xebj  /14

name: Marco Santori
tweet: There's little that even compliant companies like Kraken can do to slow the phenomenon. We have to be very, very careful about regulating in this self custody/hosted area of overlap. /13

name: Marco Santori
tweet: So, can we stop regulating crypto companies now? Of course not. But we'd better be careful. This phenomenon is outside the control of crypto companies and even governments. /12

name: Marco Santori
tweet: In this way, regulating crypto companies is completely unlike regulating traditional banks. The creation of the regulation *works against* the regulator ‚Äì both limiting the amount of available information and growing the amount of forever unavailable information. /11

name: Marco Santori
tweet: Create a regime burdensome enough and an entire shadow ecosystem springs up consisting of those who have opted out. The economy is cleaved into two: one economy that follows the rules and one with no desire or obligation to follow the rules. /10

name: Marco Santori
tweet: The more requirements you place on a monopoly, the more info you can get about its users. The more requirements you place on an opt-in service, the more costly, cumbersome and insecure the service becomes, the less people will use it and simply‚Ä¶ do it themselves instead. /9

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
Well, as a regulator you wouldn‚Äôt actually get access to the information you wanted, for one thing. 

Worse, you would *create* a bunch of information you would *never* get access to. 

Wait wut? How? /8

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
What would happen to the flow of information to the regulator if the customer didn't need any financial institution at all? 

What if the customer could just‚Ä¶ opt out and do it all themselves? /7

name: Marco Santori
tweet: What would happen, though, if the customer didn‚Äôt actually need to use the financial institution? /6

name: Marco Santori
tweet: Sure, FIs always argue that overregulation will drive business offshore where information can‚Äôt be collected. The objection is rarely persuasive. Regulation of traditional FIs almost always translates, net-net, into more information for law enforcement. /5

name: Marco Santori
tweet: After all, customers don‚Äôt really have a choice. You need a bank to send a wire. You need a check casher to turn your paycheck into dollar bills. You need a savings account to store large sums safely. You NEED financial institutions to use traditional currency effectively. /4

name: Marco Santori
tweet: Doesn‚Äôt matter if compliance is costly. Regulator still gets the info it wants. Doesn‚Äôt matter if those costs are passed on to the customer. Regulator gets its info. Makes the UX cumbersome? Doesn‚Äôt matter. Regulator gets info. Risky for users? Too bad. Regulator gets info. /3

name: Marco Santori
tweet: Regulating a traditional bank is easy: If a proposed regulation forces the bank to provide the information the regulator wants, then implement the regulation and collect the information. EZPZ. /2

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 12/ Perhaps in recognition of this, FinCEN is attempting to sneak this proposed rule into law over the holiday season - hoping nobody will notice - and even if we did, giving us only 15 days to respond.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
11/ The rule seeks to choke off resources to smart contract development, where those smart contracts are the very things that would grant access to a new, accessible financial system for those who can't afford access to today's system.

The consequences are perverse.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 10/ The rule would ALSO prohibit sending virtual currency to smart contracts that are specifically designed to eliminate the middlemen who keep the poor out of our financial system.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
9/
To be sure, the rule prohibits sending virtual currency to homeless, unhoused, and refugee populations.

But in context, it's much worse.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
8/ The consequence of this rule is clear: 

Rich people can't send money to poor people.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 7/ If the customer can't provide one - or if the ricipient doesn't have one - the FI must terminate the transaction.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 6/ Late on Friday, FinCEN proposed a new rule that would shut down this final life-saving conduit: A VCTR rule that requires FI customers to report the name and mailing address of any recipient of virtual currency.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 5/ CTRs have never required "counterparty" information. This made sense. Giving cash is, by and large, the last effective way to get money quickly and efficiently to people who don't have home addresses.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 4/ CTRs require financial institutions to collect ID info on large cash and coin (paper and metal) transactions, then report it to FinCEN. But CTRs have only ever required information about the FI‚Äôs customer.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:

Read on.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 2/ The story of this rulemaking actually starts in 2013, when Jennifer Shasky Calvery (then FinCEN Director) first suggested publicly that a VCTR ‚Äì a virtual currency transaction report ‚Äì would be valuable in fighting financial crime.

tweet: 15. So, after many months of thinking, lawing, compliancing and writing, drafting and redrafting, Kraken filed the first application to become a Wyoming Special Purpose Depository Institution, or, as I self-cringingly refer to it: A crypto bank.

16/ I'm sure the inside baseball here (of which I possess none) would be fascinating, but somber. 

Innovators want to innovate - crypto swaps are potentially game-changing products - but SEC has a mandate and there are relevant laws on the books.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 15/ Instead, according to the order, they seemed to solicit generally (including the US) from the outset, only modifying this activity once the authorities got involved. Then, during this period, still solicited broadly via promotional activity and accidentally served Americans

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
14/ Pure conjecture begins here:

If Abra had offshored the business from the beginning and never serviced or solicited US retail users, the blood pressure level at SEC would probably not be so high. 

but that wasn't what happened.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 13/ But was all of this because a handful of americans got through Abra's firewall?  Unlikely.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
12/ Apparently Abra's firewalling efforts weren't airtight and a handful (5-7?) US persons still used the service. The company ended up settling with SEC for about $150,000. 

(the Order notes that Abra generated no direct profit from the swaps)

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
11/ Abra begun offering the service again, but to users outside of the US, via a non-US entity. Not an uncommon approach.

But SEC wasn't having it.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
10/ At some point, Abra started engaging with the SEC, who presumably communicated their position that ABRA had failed to satisfy the ECP standard. Abra stopped for a couple months and dialogued with the SEC (and CFTC as well, apparently).

But that was just an intermission.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 8/ According to the SEC, Abra was only permitted to offer these swaps to "eligible contract participants" (i.e. rich people with companies, not retail investors)

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
7/ *Insert point right about here how crypto users actually care about sound money and decentralization and that's actually kind of an important difference because maybe just maybe we can change the world*

...but I digress

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 6/ From a product perspective, this strikes me as a terrific system. Retail users don't care if they actually get a security. They don't care if they're trading potato chip or microchip stock. You think they're reading 10-Ks? They're just trying to turn dollars into more dollars.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 5/ It was a pretty straightforward system: If a US user buys a stock derivative from Abra (a securities-based "swap"), then Abra takes the risk that the price of the stock goes up, but hedges the risk with a third party. ezpz lmnsqzy

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 4/ Again, nothing shady about that. What do you think Robinhood users are doing all day? So what upset the SEC?

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
3/ This in itself isn't shady of course. They were offering a "derivative" - a product that is useful for many purposes including (i) hedging and (ii) betting.

In this instance, SEC seems to take the position that it was mostly the latter.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
2/ According to the SEC's order, Abra was offering Robinhood-like securities trading, except there were no actual stocks under the hood.

Users would simply bet on the price movement of the stock without actually owning it (or owning an entitlement to it)

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 12/ It will be an uphill battle to put this into effect and if there is a final product it might look quite different than this text, but I am delighted to see new solutions being proposed.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 11/ This is bold stuff. Where the SAFT framework took the existing SAFT market practice and proposed a way to fit it into existing law, this takes the existing ICO market practice and creates *new* law that would regulate it sensibly.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 10/ Projects can sell to the public for three years without registering or relying on an exemption so long as, during that time, they publicly disclose all information material to the network. They'd still be subject to the anti-fraud laws and we'd still see enforcement activity.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 9/ "functionality" means "holders... [can] use tokens for the transmission and storage of value, to prove control over the tokens, to participate in an application running on the network, or in a manner consistent with the utility of the network."

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
8/ Peirce defines "decentralization" as 

"Not controlled and is not reasonably likely to be controlled or unilaterally changed by any single person, entity, or group of persons or entities under common control"

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
7/ Network Maturity is neither the SAFT standard of "functionality", nor the Hinman standard of "decentralization" under the proposal. It's *either* functionality *or* decentralization. 

A permissive (and sensible) approach, since networks can vary widely in practice.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 6/ There's more to it, of course. Under the proposal, A token isn't a security so long as the network has achieved "Network Maturity". What does that mean?

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 5/ If you think it's important that early investor risks ought to be taken only by those financially able to bear them, you probably won't like this proposal at all. It would resuscitate retail access to ICOs, even if in a regulated, informed, free-market manner.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: @HesterPeirce Some thoughts on the full text: https://t.co/k7DP84LMNe

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 4/If you think SAFTS just let rich people buy cheap tokens to dump expensively on poor people, you are really complaining about the accredited investor standards, so you should love this proposal. It gives retail the same early access as VCs.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 3/By and large, under the SAFT Framework that became standard in 2017/18, primary issuance of tokens in the US could only be to accredited Investors. In contrast, this safe harbor proposal permits initial sales to the public right out of the gate.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 2/ For many, this proposal is far superior to the SAFT Framework. It exempts from the registration requirements not only resales of tokens, but also *primary issuance*.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
I have reviewed the full text of the proposal. This is not an extension of the SAFT Framework at all. It is a dramatic new approach to regulating token issuance ab initio.

The SAFT Framework looks downright conservative next to this. 

1/

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 14/ Finally, this is good for regulators. Issuers still need sell pursuant to the existing securities regs. Accredited investors still bear the greatest, early risks instead of retail investors. Disclosure requirements funnel actionable data to the regulators who need it most.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 13/ This is good for retail investors. They can take informed risks, get access to new, innovative technologies, support developers whose work theyüëèactuallyüëèwantüëètoüëèuseüëè, and think the whole world will use on day, too.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 12/ This is good for venture investors. They can rely on the same environment of certainty as the developers, and they keep a seat at the head of the investment table in exchange for taking on additional risks and financing their "VC ground game"

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 11/ This is good for developers. They can raise and deploy capital in a permissionless, innovation-forward manner supported by an environment of commercial and legal certainty.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 10/ Under the proposal, these 3 years aren't free time. The developers must demonstrate that they are actually working toward decentralization, likely by way of regular disclosures to SEC.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: 9/ Peirce's proposal recognizes that this question is hard to answer at first, but gets easier to answer over time. During that time - say 3 years - developers are free to BUIDL and launch a network that just doesn't need them anymore.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
8/ How are token sellers supposed to know when they've passed this milestone?

Since it's facts-based, there's never going to be a clear answer.

Enter the safe harbor.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
7/ Legally speaking, this line is drawn when a token purchaser stops relying on the the technical and managerial expertise of the issuer/promoter for any profits she might expect.

If that seems fuzzy to you, it's for good reason. It's a difficult facts-and-circumstances test.

name: Marco Santori
tweet: @HesterPierce 6/ More to the point: When do they *stop* applying? The SAFT framework calls this line "functionality", in the famous "Hinman Speech" the SEC took that milestone and added additional factors, calling the line "decentralization".

name: Marco Santori
tweet: @HesterPierce 5/ This process is part of the SAFT Framework - all well and good. But what happens after you sell tokens to these initial investors? How do the securities laws apply then?

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
@HesterPierce 4/ Since registration doesn't make much sense for token sellers, most rely on these exemptions to sell the tokens initially.

This makes sense: (not all but) many of these early purchasers aren't buying the token to use it. They're buying it speculatively, as investors.

name: Marco Santori
tweet:
@HesterPierce 3/ Recall that, to sell securities in the US, the law requires you to register them with the SEC (e.g. an "IPO"), which is an expensive and lengthy process, or rely on an exemption.

(usually Regulation D for private placements to accredited investors, or Reg S for offshore sales

Could it really be that simple? Read on.
